# Four-bar linkage skeleton (std.mech.mechanisms.FourBar, WO-53).
# Fill in the four link lengths and the ground/output pivot roles this
# mechanism connects; `regolith doc` renders the pattern's datasheet
# (params, promises, coupler law, citations).
#
# HONEST ENGINE GAP (verified empirically, WO-53 template audit):
# instantiating ANY pattern generic (`FourBar<...=free, ...>` here)
# emits an unresolved `conforms` obligation that
# `orchestrator/translate.py` always defers with
# `conformance_windows_unresolved` -- refinement-bound extraction for
# pattern generics is a named WO-12 engine cut, not specific to this
# template or these link lengths. `regolith build --release` /
# `regolith ship` therefore cannot succeed for ANY `four_bar`-scaffolded
# project until WO-12 lands, regardless of what other claims the file
# carries.
import std.mech.mechanisms (FourBar)

assembly Linkage:
    connect:
        link: FourBar<ground=free, input=free, coupler=free, output=free>(
                  a=ground_pivot, b=output_pivot)

# Second, clearly-marked claim (independent of the pattern above): a
# real, honestly-dischargeable structural check on one link arm, so the
# discharge machinery and build report stay meaningful even though the
# overall release gate is blocked by the WO-12 gap noted above.
# k = 3*E*I/L^3 ~= 1.65e5 N/m for these numbers; floor set below that.
part LinkageArm:
    loads:
        e_modulus: [69e9, 69e9]
        i_area: [8.3e-9, 8.3e-9]
        length: [0.5, 0.5]

    require Structural:
        mech.stiffness: >= 5000
